@bingwang-ms I add a breakpoint after setup ACL table in this testcase, then got below message from DUT:

From `sonic-db-cli`:

```
$ sonic-db-cli CONFIG_DB keys \* | grep ACL_TABLE_TYPE
ACL_TABLE_TYPE|CUSTOM_TYPE
$ sonic-db-cli CONFIG_DB hgetall "ACL_TABLE_TYPE|CUSTOM_TYPE"
{'MATCHES@': 'DST_IP,DST_IPV6,ETHER_TYPE,IP_TYPE,IP_PROTOCOL,NEXT_HEADER,L4_SRC_PORT,L4_DST_PORT,L4_SRC_PORT_RANGE,L4_DST_PORT_RANGE', 'BIND_POINTS@': 'PORT', 'ACTIONS@': 'PACKET_ACTION,COUNTER'}
```

From `show run all`:
```json
 "ACL_TABLE_TYPE": {
 "CUSTOM_TYPE": {
 "ACTIONS": [
 "PACKET_ACTION",
 "COUNTER"
 ],
 "BIND_POINTS": [
 "PORT"
 ],
 "MATCHES": [
 "DST_IP",
 "DST_IPV6",
 "ETHER_TYPE",
 "IP_TYPE",
 "IP_PROTOCOL",
 "NEXT_HEADER",
 "L4_SRC_PORT",
 "L4_DST_PORT",
 "L4_SRC_PORT_RANGE",
 "L4_DST_PORT_RANGE"
 ]
 }
 }
```

@bingwang-ms @Blueve 

When I use **string** in custom ACL table type, `sonic-db-cli` returns:

```
$ sonic-db-cli CONFIG_DB keys \* | grep ACL_TABLE_TYPE
ACL_TABLE_TYPE|CUSTOM_TYPE
$ sonic-db-cli CONFIG_DB hgetall "ACL_TABLE_TYPE|CUSTOM_TYPE"
{'MATCHES': 'DST_IP,DST_IPV6,ETHER_TYPE,IP_TYPE,IP_PROTOCOL,NEXT_HEADER,L4_SRC_PORT,L4_DST_PORT,L4_SRC_PORT_RANGE,L4_DST_PORT_RANGE', 'ACTIONS': 'PACKET_ACTION,COUNTER', 'BIND_POINTS': 'PORT'}
```

When I use **list** in custom ACL table type, `sonic-db-cli` shows:

```
$ sonic-db-cli CONFIG_DB keys \* | grep ACL_TABLE_TYPE
ACL_TABLE_TYPE|CUSTOM_TYPE
$ sonic-db-cli CONFIG_DB hgetall "ACL_TABLE_TYPE|CUSTOM_TYPE"
{'MATCHES@': 'DST_IP,DST_IPV6,ETHER_TYPE,IP_TYPE,IP_PROTOCOL,NEXT_HEADER,L4_SRC_PORT,L4_DST_PORT,L4_SRC_PORT_RANGE,L4_DST_PORT_RANGE', 'BIND_POINTS@': 'PORT', 'ACTIONS@': 'PACKET_ACTION,COUNTER'}
```

Comparing the output of `sonic-db-cli`, we can we the only difference is the keys of the dict has an extra `@` when we use list. The values are same. According to [sonic-swss/orchagent/aclorch.cpp#L663](https://github.com/sonic-net/sonic-swss/blob/master/orchagent/aclorch.cpp#L663), `orchagent` simply split the string with `,`. That's why it can be compatible with both formats.
